{{DEFAULTSORT:American Civil Liberties Union of Ohio and The Rev. Matthew Peterson v. Capitol Square Review and Advisory Board}}
[[Category:Establishment Clause case law]]

[[File:HUDact69-cover.png|thumb|Cover of the Housing and Urban Development Act of 1969]] “'''Brooke Amendment'''” is the common name for section 213 (a) of the Housing and Urban Development Act of 1969 (Public Law 91-152) that was sponsored by Senator [[Edward Brooke III]] (R-MA), which capped rent in [[public housing]] projects at 25% of tenant’s income. It amended section 2(1), paragraph two, of the US [[Housing Act of 1937]], and was enacted on [[Christmas Eve]], 24 December 1969.<ref name="HUD Act 69">{{cite web|title=Housing and urban development act of 1969 ;Public law 91-152 and section-by-section summary.|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=uc1.a0000107235;view=1up;seq=4|website=Hathi Trust|publisher=Washington :|accessdate=3 May 2017|date=1 January 1969}}</ref><ref name="HUD.gov">{{cite web|title=Major Legislation on Housing and Urban Development Enacted Since 1932|url=https://portal.hud.gov/hudportal/documents/huddoc?id=Legs_Chron_June2014.pdf|website=Housing and Urban Development|accessdate=3 May 2017}}</ref> The Brooke Amendment became the first instance of the benchmark to measure housing affordability, which became known as the "30 percent rule of thumb"<ref>{{cite web|title=Rental Burdens: Rethinking Affordability Measures {{!}} HUD USER|url=https://www.huduser.gov/portal/pdredge/pdr_edge_featd_article_092214.html|website=www.huduser.gov|accessdate=7 May 2017|language=en}}</ref> in 1981 when the 25 percent cap was raised to 30 percent of tenant income.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://apps.americanbar.org/abastore/products/books/abstracts/5530024%20chapter%201_abs.pdf|title=Affordable Housing: an intimate history|last=Edson|first=Charles L.|date=2011|website=American Bar Association|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=3 May 2017}}</ref>
Senator Brooke advocated for two other subsections that were enacted in the Housing and Urban Development Act of 1969. Section 213 (b) gives the Secretary of [[Housing and Urban Development]] (HUD) authority to revoke the 25 percent cap if it results in a reduction of total welfare assistance. Section 213 (c) amends section 14 of the [[Housing Act of 1937]] to ensure the "low-rent character of public housing projects" by fixing annual contract contributions according to the current Federal rate of interest.<ref name="HUD Act 69" /> Together, the three subsections can be referred to as the "Brooke Amendments",<ref>{{cite book|title=The legal guide to affordable housing development|date=2011|publisher=American Bar Association|isbn=9781616329839|edition=2nd|location=Chicago, Ill.|pages=chapter 1 - Affordable Housing: an intimate history|last1=Edson|first1=Charles L.}}</ref> although the pluralized term is less common.
