{{for|the band|Guaranteed Irish (band)}}
{{ad|date=June 2018}}
[[File:Guaranteed Irish logo.png|thumb|61px|The version of the Guaranteed Irish logo used in 2000s.]]
'''Guaranteed Irish''' is an Irish [[nonprofit organisation|nonprofit business membership organisation]] representing indigenous and international businesses operating in Ireland. The Guaranteed Irish symbol is awarded to companies which create "quality" jobs, contribute to local communities and are "committed to Irish provenance". 

The members of Guaranteed Irish span all sectors including pharmaceutical; healthcare; technology; construction; energy; professional services; tourism; food and drink; art and design; retail; and more. When assessing an applicant for membership, the Appraisals Board of Guaranteed Irish looks at three core criteria; ''jobs, community and provenance''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.guaranteedirish.ie/membership/|title=Become a Member {{!}} Guaranteed Irish|date=2017-08-01|work=Guaranteed Irish|access-date=2018-05-03|language=en-US}}</ref>''.''

According to research published in February 2018, member companies of Guaranteed Irish directly employed 49,873 people in Ireland and generated a turnover of €11bn in Ireland in 2017. Globally, these companies generated a turnover of €25.84bn in 2017, with 46% of members exporting, primarily to the UK, US and mainland Europe.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.guaranteedirish.ie/news/guaranteed-irish-month-launched-at-irish-stock-exchange/|title='Guaranteed Irish Month' launched at ISE {{!}} Guaranteed Irish|date=2018-02-07|work=Guaranteed Irish|access-date=2018-05-03|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/business/economy/guaranteed-irish-companies-generated-11bn-in-revenues-last-year-1.3383358|title=‘Guaranteed Irish’ companies generated €11bn in revenues last year|work=The Irish Times|access-date=2018-05-03|language=en-US}}</ref>

Over four decades, the Guaranteed Irish symbol has become one of the most recognised symbols in the country.{{cn|date=June 2018}} Member companies can use the Guaranteed Irish symbol, a stylised overlay of the letters "g" and "i", on packaging and marketing materials for products and services certified by the organisation as having Irish origin or where at least 50% added value takes place in Ireland.

Through the use of the Guaranteed Irish symbol, in addition to PR and marketing campaigns, networking events, business seminars, and lobbying activities, Guaranteed Irish assists its members to expand at home and abroad, contributing to Ireland’s reputation for quality goods and services, and showcasing Ireland as best-in-class for business.{{cn|date=June 2018}}

The original Guaranteed Irish campaign was developed from December 1974 by the [[Irish Goods Council]], originally the Working Group on the Promotion and Sale of Irish Goods within the National Development Association, which was incorporated separately in 1978.<ref>{{cite book|url=http://opac.oireachtas.ie/AWData/Library3/Library2/DL018443.pdf#page=12|title=Ninth Annual Report to December 31st 1975|last=National Development Association (Forbairt)|first=|year=1976|series=Official publications|volume=Prl.5990|location=Dublin|pages=12–13|chapter=The Working Group|format=PDF|accessdate=9 January 2014}}</ref> The Council's first director, [[Vivian Murray]], was instrumental in the campaign.<ref name="it1224242845920">{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/obituaries/2009/0314/1224242845920.html|title=Goods Council chief executive who created Buy Irish scheme|last=|first=|date=14 March 2009|work=[[Irish Times]]|accessdate=5 April 2009|publisher=}}</ref><ref name="rte">{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2009/0306/murrayv-business.html|title=Businessman Vivian Murray dies at 76|last=|first=|date=6 March 2009|work=[[RTÉ]]|accessdate=4 April 2009|publisher=}}</ref>  Spending on the campaign increased from £90,376 in 1976 to £361,491 in 1981.<ref>{{cite book|url=http://opac.oireachtas.ie/AWData/Library3/Library2/DL022834.pdf#page=12|title=Annual Report 1977|author=Irish Goods Council|date=15 December 1978|publisher=Department of Industry and Commerce|series=Official publications|volume=Prl.7596|chapter=Schedule to the Accounts|accessdate=9 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=http://opac.oireachtas.ie/AWData/Library3/Library2/DL040379.pdf#page=10|title=Annual Report 1982|author=Irish Goods Council|date=21 December 1983|publisher=Department of Industry, Commerce and Energy|series=Official publications|volume=Pl.2040.|chapter=INCOME AND EXPENDITURE ACCOUNT For year ending 31/12/1982|accessdate=9 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://oireachtasdebates.oireachtas.ie/debates%20authoring/DebatesWebPack.nsf/takes/seanad1978070600005#N182|title=Green Paper: Development for Full Employment: Motion (Resumed).|year=1983|work=Seanad Éireann debates|accessdate=8 January 2014}}</ref> In 1980, 1,000 companies were participating.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://debates.oireachtas.ie/seanad/1980/12/10/00009.asp#N27|title=Sale of Irish Goods: Motion.|date=10 December 1980|work=Seanad Éireann debates|accessdate=8 January 2014}}</ref> In 1982, the [[European Court of Justice]] ruled that, since the Irish Goods Council received state funding, its Guaranteed Irish campaign contravened the [[Treaty of Rome]]'s rules against [[protectionism]].<ref name="eurlex">{{cite journal|year=1982|title=Case 249/81 Commission of the European Communities v Ireland. Judgment of the Court of 24 November 1982.|url=http://eur-lex.europa.eu/smartapi/cgi/sga_doc?smartapi!celexplus!prod!CELEXnumdoc&lg=en&numdoc=61981J0249|journal=European Court Reports|page=4005}}</ref> As a consequence the campaign was separated from the Irish Goods Council into an independent nonprofit organisation, Guaranteed Irish Limited, which does not receive state funding.<ref name="buj2008">{{cite web|url=http://debates.oireachtas.ie/BUJ/2008/11/12/00004.asp|title=Promoting Irish-Made Products: Discussion with Guaranteed Irish.|author=Joint Committee on Enterprise, Trade and Employment|date=12 November 2008|work=Oireachtas proceedings|accessdate=8 January 2014}}</ref> It was launched in 1984 by [[Patrick Hillery]], then [[President of Ireland]].

In 2017, led by a new CEO, Brid O’Connell, and a new Board of Directors and team, the organisation rebranded and repositioned by opening up membership to international companies operating in Ireland. Guaranteed Irish was relaunched by the [[Taoiseach]], [[Enda Kenny]], in March 2017, using the original logo from the campaign’s inception. 

In February, the inaugural Guaranteed Irish Month, to take place each March, was unveiled at the [[Irish Stock Exchange]] by [[Ciarán Cannon|Ciaran Cannon]], T.D., Minister of State at the [[Department of Foreign Affairs and Trade (Ireland)|Department of Foreign Affairs and Trade]] with special responsibility for the Diaspora and International Development, and Deirdre Somers, CEO of the Irish Stock Exchange.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rte.ie/news/business/2018/0207/938926-march-designated-guaranteed-irish-month/|title=March designated 'Guaranteed Irish month'|date=2018-02-07|work=RTE.ie|access-date=2018-05-03|language=en}}</ref>

As a non-profit organisation, Guaranteed Irish is entirely funded through membership fees which is used to actively promote Guaranteed Irish businesses through online and offline PR and marketing activities<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.guaranteedirish.ie/who-we-are/|title=Who We Are {{!}} Guaranteed Irish|date=2017-08-01|work=Guaranteed Irish|access-date=2018-05-03|language=en-US}}</ref>. The organisation currently has 300 members with plans to increase the number of member companies to 500 by the end of 2018. In April 2018, Guaranteed Irish launched a new website.

Guaranteed Irish is the national symbol for provenance and trust.{{cn|date=June 2018}}

